[[zh:铌]]

[[File:Molybdenum_crystaline_fragment_and_1cm3_cube.jpg|thumb|crystaline molybdenum and a 1cm<sup>3</sup> cube]] '''Molybdenum''' is a [[chemical element]]. It has the chemical symbol '''Mo'''. It has the [[atomic number]] 42. It has 35 IsOTopEs. The name Molybdenum is from the [[Greek language|Greek]] meaning "leadlike". The [[color]] of [[purity|pure]] molybdenum is silvery-white. It does not occur naturally, and is made from [[molybdenite]].<ref name=per> {{cite web |url=http://periodic.lanl.gov/elements/42.html |title=Molybdenum |publisher=periodic.lanl.gov |accessdate=2009-06-20 |last= |first= }} </ref>
== Uses == It is used in [[alloy]]s with other metals like [[stainless steel]]. It helps to make metal stronger, especially in high temperatures, and makes it less likely to rust.<ref name=rt> {{cite web |url=http://www.riotinto.com/whatweproduce/452_other_minerals.asp |title=Molybdenum - Rio Tinto |publisher=www.riotinto.com |accessdate=2009-06-20 |last= |first= }} </ref> This makes it good for use in high speed tools, such as [[drill]]s and [[saw]] [[blade]]s.<ref name=rt/> It is used in [[aircraft]] and [[missile]] parts, as well as in [[nuclear reactor]]s.<ref name=per/> It is also not [[toxic]], so it is used in making metal [[bowl]]s for use in making [[food]], [[medicine]]s and other [[chemical]]s.<ref name=rt/>
== History == Molybdenum was used for many years before it was identified in 1778 by Swedish scientist, [[Carl Wilhelm Scheele]]. In 1782, [[Peter Jacob Hjelm]] was able to separate it into a dark powder he called "molybdenum".<ref> {{cite web |url=http://www.rsc.org/chemsoc/visualelements/pages/molybdenum.html |title=Visual Elements - Molybdenum |publisher=www.rsc.org |accessdate=2009-06-20 |last= |first= }} </ref> It was first mined in 1916 at Climax, near [[Leadville]], in [[Colorado]].<ref> {{cite web |url=http://www.imoa.info/molybdenum/mining_processing/moly_mining_processing.html |title=Molybdenum Mining & Processing |publisher=www.imoa.info |accessdate=2009-06-20 |last= |first= }} </ref>
